phasis on political opportunities in recent research, and the extent to which opportunity models ignore the cultural and emotional triggers for collective action. By examining new directions in the study of protest and contention, this book shows that although political opportunities can help explain the emergence of certain kinds of movements, a new strategic language can ultimately tell us far more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPolitical science. 0aProtest movements. 0aSocial movements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aGoodwin, Jeff, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJasper, James M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477893040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778930423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778930.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles